\ud83d\udc06\n\nLua and Khan, our two newest jaguars, are beginning introductions with one another. Our team is thrilled with how well they are both doing together. \n\nIt is typical for these big cats to be territorial of their space, especially females. Both of Lua and Khan's responses to one another are normal and expected for their species, although it can look a bit intense to the human eye. Our animal care team monitors their behaviors closely during each of their visits, and we hope to increase the time they're spending together. Eventually, we hope these two can coexist comfortably in the same habitat. \n\nLua and Khan are a recommended breeding pair through the Association of Zoos and Aquariums' Species Survival Program. It's been over ten years since we've welcomed jaguar cubs at our Zoo, and we would love to continue our legacy of helping this species' population grow. We hope to share more updates with you another update to our seagrass restoration progress! \ud83c\udf3fWe\u2019ve teamed up with the Florida Institute of Technology (FIT) and the University of Central Florida (UCF) to study how Caulerpa, a type of local algae,  affects seagrass growth. Funding for this work is through the Florida Seagrass Restoration Technology Development Initiative in partnership with the FDEP and Mote Marine Laboratory. This is essential to our work to revitalize the Indian River Lagoon, as it provides insight into how to best approach seagrass restoration. \n\nDuring Phase 1 of this project, we found that algae growth can affect sediments and impact seagrass growth when in excess. However, we still needed to assess why this change affects seagrass growth. This is where Phase 2 comes in! \ud83d\udc47\n\nDuring Phase 2, our ROS team, FIT and UCF are collecting routine data from across our planted seagrass sites, gathering water quality information (salinity, pH, turbidity, sediment characteristics) and information about the seagrass and algae including what types of microbes live with them. On top of this field work, we\u2019re also performing lab experiments planting seagrass in different sediments. Coupling these results will give us the best idea of how Caulerpa growth and abundance affect seagrass growth in the Indian River Lagoon and where is best to place planted seagrass. \n\nThank you to our dedicated Restore Our Shores team for their hardworking hours in the summer sun to help restore our lagoon.\u2764\ufe0f It\u2019s efforts like these that can make a
